The `show` method is an alias for the `print` function, which will output a string representation of your struct.
\end{blockquote}

I've tried:

\begin{code}
function show(io::IO, fwu::FloatWithUnits)
    print("$fwu.value")
    print("$fwu.unit")
end
\end{code}

but that doesn't work and I can't seem to figure out how to concatenate these two fields together (so `1.8 meters`).

Comment: Please show your attempts, as well as the result you got from it

Answer: \begin{blockquote}

`print("$fwu.value")`
\end{blockquote}

This is a string interpolation of an expression that calls the `print` function on the variable `fwu`. Since this is not what you want to do, you can just use `show`, like so:

\begin{code}
function show(io::IO, fwu::FloatWithUnits)
    println("$fwu.value $fwu.unit")
end
\end{code}

The code above will output

\begin{code}
1.8 meters
\end{code}
